title: Railroad - Pragmas

! Pragmas -- Railroad Diagrams

This tiddler presents the same pragma syntax as [[EBNF - Pragmas]], but using railroad diagrams for visual clarity. Follow the tracks left-to-right to see valid syntax paths.

Pragmas appear at the very beginning of tiddler content, before any rendered output. They configure the parser or define procedures, functions, and widgets. Once a non-pragma line is encountered, pragma parsing stops.

!! Pragma Block

A tiddler may begin with zero or more consecutive pragmas:

<$railroad text="""
\start none
\end none
[{ ("\procedure" | "\function" | "\widget" | "\define" | "\import" | "\parameters" | "\whitespace" | "\parsermode" | "\rules" | <"comment">) }]
"""/>

---

!! Parameter Definitions (shared)

Several pragmas share the same parameter-list syntax. A parameter list is enclosed in parentheses, with parameters separated by commas or spaces.

!!! Parameter List

<$railroad text="""
\start none
\end none
"(" [{ <"param-def"> +("," | <"space">) }] ")"
"""/>

!!! Individual Parameter

Each parameter has a name and an optional default value, separated by a colon.

<$railroad text="""
\start none
\end none
<"param-name"> [":" <"default-value">]
"""/>

!!! Default Value

Default values may be triple-quoted, double-quoted, single-quoted, or unquoted. Unquoted values include MVV references like `((varname))`.

<$railroad text=`
\start none
\end none
( '"""' <"text"> '"""'
| '"' <"text"> '"'
| "'" <"text"> "'"
| <"unquoted-value">
)
`/>

---

!! `\procedure` / `\function` / `\widget`

The modern definition pragmas. All three share the same structure -- only the keyword differs. See [[fnprocdef.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/fnprocdef.js]] for the implementation.

* ''`\procedure`'' -- defines reusable wikitext. Parameters are accessed as variables with `<<paramName>>`.
* ''`\function`'' -- defines a filter function. The body is a filter expression.
* ''`\widget`'' -- defines a custom widget. The name must start with `$` (e.g. `$my.widget`).

!!! Single-line form

The entire definition fits on one line, terminated by a linefeed.

<$railroad text="""
"\" ("procedure" | "function" | "widget") <"space"> <"name"> <"(params)"> [:" "] <"body"> "lf"
"""/>

!!! Multiline form

The body spans multiple lines. The first line ends after the closing parenthesis; `\end` terminates the body.

<$railroad text="""
"\" ("procedure" | "function" | "widget") <"space"> <"name"> <"(params)"> "lf" <"body"> "\end" [<"name">] "lf"
"""/>

* <<.place name>> is a sequence of non-whitespace characters other than `(`.
* <<.place body>> is any wikitext (may include nested definitions).
* <<.place params>> uses the shared parameter-list syntax above.

---

!! `\define` (legacy)

<<.deprecated-since "5.3.0" "Use `\procedure` instead.">>

The original macro definition pragma. Uses textual substitution: `$paramname$` for parameter references and `$(varname)$` for variable substitution. See [[macrodef.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/macrodef.js]].

!!! Single-line form

<$railroad text="""
"\define" <"space"> <"name"> <"(params)"> [:" "] <"body"> "lf"
"""/>

!!! Multiline form

<$railroad text="""
"\define" <"space"> <"name"> <"(params)"> "lf" <"body"> "\end" [<"name">] "lf"
"""/>

`\define` also supports `[[double bracket]]` quoting for default values, which `\procedure` does not.

---

!! `\import`

Imports variable definitions from other tiddlers. The argument is a filter expression whose output tiddlers are imported. See [[import.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/import.js]].

<$railroad text="""
"\import" <"space"> <"filter-expression"> "lf"
"""/>

All procedures, functions, widgets, and macros defined in the matching tiddlers become available in the current tiddler.

---

!! `\parameters`

Declares parameters with optional defaults for the current tiddler when transcluded or used as a procedure/widget body. See [[parameters.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/parameters.js]].

<$railroad text="""
"\parameters" [:" "] <"(params)"> "lf"
"""/>

The parameter list uses the same shared syntax described above. This pragma is useful for tiddlers that serve as templates -- it documents and provides defaults for the expected inputs.

---

!! `\whitespace`

Controls whether the parser trims whitespace from the output. See [[whitespace.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/whitespace.js]].

<$railroad text="""
"\whitespace" <"space"> ("trim" | :"notrim") "lf"
"""/>

`trim` removes runs of whitespace from the rendered output -- useful in templates and procedures. `notrim` (the default) preserves whitespace.

---

!! `\parsermode`

Switches the parser between block mode and inline mode. See [[parsermode.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/parsermode.js]].

<$railroad text="""
"\parsermode" <"space"> (:"block" | "inline") "lf"
"""/>

By default, content is parsed in block mode. Switching to `inline` prevents block-level constructs (headings, lists) and avoids unwanted `<p>` wrapping.

---

!! `\rules`

Enables or disables specific parser rules for the remainder of the tiddler. See [[rules.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/rules.js]].

<$railroad text="""
"\rules" <"space"> ("only" | "except") <"space"> {<"rule-name"> + <"space">}
"""/>

* ''`only`'' -- disables all rules except those listed.
* ''`except`'' -- keeps all rules active except those listed.

---

!! HTML Comments

HTML comments are recognised as pragmas when they appear in the pragma area. They are silently consumed, allowing annotation between pragmas. See [[commentblock.js|$:/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/commentblock.js]].

<$railroad text="""
"<!--" <"comment-text"> "-->"
"""/>
